<p>
	I have spoken with many first-time entrepreneurs that have the same question: how do I make sure I have good investors? What differentiates a good investor from a bad investor? It’s a really great question, and many times you hear that “it’s just a gut feeling”.
</p>
<p>
	Is this true? Yes. Raising money and finding investors to partner with is a bit like dating - you shouldn’t get into a long term relationship with someone you don’t feel comfortable spending 7-10 years with. But, there’s more to understanding the differences.
</p>

<p>
	I find Dave Lambert and Right Side Capital to be refreshingly “right” in terms of their approach to startups and investment. I asked Dave to share his thoughts on Right Side’s investment strategy and mentality. He had some great advice to give entrepreneurs looking to raise capital. In this article we will cover advice Dave has on relationship expectations with investors, how to think about fundraising in the eyes of an investor, and when to say no to money.
</p>


<h4>Meet Dave Lambert and Right Side Capital</h4>
